pgTitle: List of steamboats on the Yukon River

rows.text: Risdon Iron Works (hull); James H. Calvert (superstructure)
Sold to John J. McKenna in 1898. Wrecked and abandoned in 1920.
Alaska Union Mining Co. (of Chicago, Illinois)
Sold to Elbridge T. “E.T.” Barnette and Charles Smith in 1901. Later in 1901, Foundered at St. Michael.
Not inspected. Registry closed between July 1902 & June 1903.
Owned by Clarence D. Flanagan. Foundered on the Upper Tanana River in 1916.
Operated on the Lower Yukon River. Last inspected in 1903. Listed in Jones (1904). Aurum is the Latin word for gold.
Lewis Stenger and A. H. Willock
Owned by William McCamant in 1925. Abandoned between July 1926 & June 1927.
Owned by Isaac Burpee (ca. 1875-1951). Registry closed in 1914.
Owned by William Daniels. Abandoned between July 1923 & June 1924.
Owned by Carl C. White (1880-1933). Abandoned at Fairbanks in 1926.
Owned by Wenthrop Mining & Trading Co. (of Pennsylvania). Last inspected in 1903. Listed in Jones (1904). Registry closed between July 1908 & June 1909.
Originally owned by John Myers (of Chicago Alaska Transportation Co.). Last inspected in 1898. Sold to Donald Smith in 1899. Registry closed in 1900.

Originally owned by the Tanana Trading Co. Sold to the North American Transportation & Trading Co. and, then, to the Merchants’ Yukon Transportation Co. in 1906. Foundered after striking an object at Tolovana, Alaska in 1909. Named for Ella Bratnober (1856–1947), wife of Henry.

Originally owned by William J. Rant. Machinery removed from boat in 1899. Sold to John H. Tulley in 1903. Resold to Arthur J. Simonds in 1904. Resold back to Rant by 1907. Wrecked and abandoned. Registry closed in 1920.
Risdon Iron Works (hull); James H. Calvert (superstructure)

Originally owned by Upper Yukon Co. Sold to Henry Alexander Munn in 1899. Retired in 1900. Abandoned in 1901. Remains scrapped in 1999. Named for Frank H. Kilbourne (1857–1928), Seattle, Washington businessman.

Originally owned by Seattle-Yukon Transportation Co. Sold to Hoey V. V. Bean in 1899. Sold to Capt. Sydney C. Barrington in 1900. Later in 1900, it foundered in the “Thirtymile” section of the Yukon River. Sold to Capt. Wallace Langley in 1904. Owned by A. D. Wright by 1912. Out of documentation, 1914 to 1938. Converted to barge and owned by George S. Black by 1939. Foundered on the Yukon River near Galena, Alaska, in 1952.

Originally owned by Klondike Promotion Co. (of Chicago). Sold to Minor W. Bruce in 1904. Last inspected in 1904. Registry closed between July 1909 and June 1910. Named for Helen Bruce (1898–1988), daughter of Alaskan fur trader Minor W. Bruce.

Originally owned by Logan. Sold to Independent Mining Co. in 1899. Sold to Tanana Trading Co. and converted to a wrecking barge in 1905. Resold to North American Transportation & Trading Co., then transferred to the Merchants’ Yukon Transportation Co. in 1906. Sold to Northern Navigation Co. in 1911. Sold to White Pass in 1914. Not used under White Pass ownership. Abandoned in 1917.
Owned by a company of Indiana men. Last inspected in 1899. Registry closed between July 1900 & June 1901.
Operated on the Lower Yukon River. Last inspected in 1900. Listed in Jones (1904).
Originally owned by James Domville. Sold to the Klondike, Yukon & Stewart River Co. in 1899. Later in 1899, it was wrecked in the “Thirtymile” section of the Yukon River.
Operated on Upper Yukon River. Owned by Kalamazoo Mining & Prospecting Co. Foundered at Casey’s Rock, Thirtymile in 1898.
Operated on the Lower Yukon River. Sold to Dave Cohn and S. M. Hirsch in 1899. Last inspected in 1900. Listed in Jones (1904).
Owned by Amos J. Tucker. Registry closed between July 1919 & June 1920.
Operated on the Lower Yukon River. Last inspected in 1900. Listed in Jones (1904).
Rebuilt by Joseph Supple for Daly & Co. (Skagway, Alaska) in 1898. Sold to George Findlay in 1900. Resold to Edward W. G. "Ted" Tennant in 1901. Resold to John Leech in 1902. Registry closed in 1920.

Originally owned by British-American Steamship Co. Sold to the Alaska Meat Co. in 1899. Alaska Meat became Pacific Cold Storage Co. in 1900. Boat sold to Waechter Bros. in 1905 or 1906. Demolished by fire at Fairbanks, Alaska in 1906. Named for Lotta Talbot (1889–1971), daughter of Richard A.
Purchased by U.S. Army in 1900. Gone in 1902 or 1903.
Originally owned by Teslin Transportation Co. Sold to Henry C. Lisle by 1907. Abandoned in 1914.

Originally owned by Alaska Exploration Co. Transferred to Northern Navigation Co. in 1901. Sold to M. E. Dawson between 1907 & 1909. Sold to Henry M. H. Bolander between 1910 & 1912. Abandoned between July 1922 & June 1929.
Not known whether sternwheel or screw propeller propulsion.

Originally owned by the Milwaukee-Alaska Gold-Dredge Mining Co. Sold to the British-American Steamship Co. in 1899. Resold to the Seattle-Yukon Transportation Co. in 1900. Transferred to Northern Navigation Co. in 1901. Sold between 1908 & 1912. Abandoned between July 1924 & June 1925.

Originally owned by Stewart River Navigation Co. Sold to the Side Streams Navigation Co. in 1909. Wrecked by ice at Dawson City, Yukon in 1915. Named for Pauline E. Dow, née Raymond (1898-1978), daughter of Nathaniel.
Owned by George S. Black. Abandoned between July 1930 & June 1931.
Owned by Frederick J. Currier. Stranded off the Chena River in 1900.

Owned by Capt. Wallace Langley and John E. Green by 1911. Owned by Charles E. Lake by 1912. Sold to William P. McKeague, Harvey Watson, and Roy Henderson in 1913. Abandoned between July 1935 & June 1936. Pup was a term that was current during the Klondike Gold Rush, which referred to a second order streamlet that was a tributary to yet another stream.

Originally owned by Robert C. Smith. Sold to Emil Stauf and H. E. Ridley in 1901. Resold to Thomas Smith in 1905. Resold to Capt. A. F. Daughtry and George Waltenberg in 1908. Registry closed in 1914.
Sold to Adelbert E. Claflin in 1899. Sold to John S. Segers in 1903. Sold to the Kuskokwim Commercial Co. in 1905. Sold to the Alaska Rivers Navigation Co. between 1917 & 1925. Abandoned in 1938.
Owned by Daniel Cadzow. Registry closed in 1936. Name describes the 20-mile canyon, located 7 to 27 miles northeast (upstream) of Tanana, through which the Yukon River flows.
Originally owned by Redlands-Alaska Mining Co. For sale in 1899. Listed in Jones (1904). Registry closed between July 1913 & June 1914.

Originally owned by the British-American Steamship Co. Sold to the Alaska Meat Co. in 1899. Alaska Meat became Pacific Cold Storage Co. in 1900. Boat resold to Waechter Bros. in 1919. Abandoned between July 1934 & June 1935.
Raymond Brumbaugh, Henry C. Hamilton & Edward E. Kellogg
Owned by Edward Simon. Abandoned between July 1932 & June 1933. Named for Selma Simon (b. 1860), wife of Edward.
Originally steam powered. Obtained by Klondike Airways about 1929. Subsequently converted to gasoline power. Retired in 1938.
Last inspected in 1899. Registry closed between July 1899 & June 1900. Named for Thomas J. Nestor (1862-1943).
Originally, gasoline powered-sternwheeler, owned by Capt. Wallace Langley. Converted to steam power in 1906. Sold to Alaska Rivers Navigation Co. in 1933. Abandoned in 1940.

Originally owned by John W. Rock, William Wilcox, and Thomas Harrison. Sold to Yukon Exploration & Trading Co. in 1897. Returned to California in 1899. Registry closed between July 1916 & June 1917. Named for Capt. Thomas Dwyer (1835-1890).
Operated on the Upper Yukon River.
